First, we imported the libraries we needed to create a decision tree, load the data, and plot the decision tree:

In [1]:
# import appropriate libraries
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.tree import plot_tree
import pandas as pd
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

There were two instances of the names Joe, Frank, Charles, and Paul so we modified the dataset to make every person unique.

We also encountered issues with Hans, so we modified the "LookingStraight" feature so that the model could classify him.

We also removed some redundant features from the initial dataset. Doing so, we were able to reduce the amount of steps to classify each person

Second, we created the model, loaded in the final dataset, and split the data into the independent variables and the dependent variable we are trying to predict:

In [2]:
# create the classifier and load in the data
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
df = pd.read_csv('picojosh_dataset.csv')

# split the data into independent and dependent variables
X = df.iloc[:,1:]
y = df['ID']

Finally, we fit the data to the model and plotted the final decision tree:

In [3]:
# fit the model to the data
clf.fit(X,y)

# set the size of the figure
plt.figure(figsize=(90, 60))

# plot the decision tree
plot_tree(clf,
          filled=True,
          rounded=True,
          fontsize=10,
          class_names=y,
          feature_names= ["Male", "FacialHair",	"Bald", "Hat", "Glasses", "BlueEyes", "BlondeHair", "BlackHair","OrangeHair","BrownHair","WhiteHair","LookingStraight",	"FatLips","Frowning","CurlyHair","RosyCheeks","CleftChin", "MiddlePart", "SidePart", "LargeNose", "LongHair", "Kid", "Glasses"]
)
plt.show()
